INSERT INTO public.posts (slug,title,subtitle,category,country,tags,content_html,status,published_at,author_name) VALUES
('not-taking-yourself-seriously','On not taking yourself seriously','The quietest discipline in business is forgetting your own importance for an hour.','Personal Philosophy','cambodia',ARRAY['awareness','work','nondual']::text[],'<p>The strongest people I work with in Cambodia share one habit. They do not perform themselves.</p><p>Patrick walks the Moo Moo Farm in the same shirt every week. Mr. Chan Ang sits at the BRM mill in Kampong Thom and does the count himself when he wants to be sure. Om Dhavy runs operations and never raises her voice. None of them are quiet because they are humble. They are quiet because they are working.</p><p>I notice the opposite in myself when a meeting goes sideways. The mind starts rehearsing what I should have said. It writes the email I will send tomorrow. It builds a small case in my defense. None of that is the work. The work was the meeting and the meeting is over.</p><p>The nondual lens helps here. There is no separate person who needs defending. There is a meeting that went a certain way, and now there is a next step. The story about how I performed in the meeting is added on top, after the fact, and it costs an hour I could spend on the next step.</p><p>This is not detachment. I still care. I still lose sleep over the rice harvest and the Atlanta sell-through and the next round of investor calls. The difference is that the caring is not built on a fragile sense of who I am. The work gets to be the work.</p><p>If you want a test for whether you are taking yourself too seriously in business, try this. After a hard call, ask yourself what you would advise a friend in the same situation. The answer comes out clean and fast. The advice you give yourself, after a hard call, comes out tangled. That is the gap. The gap is the cost of taking yourself seriously.</p><p>Build the businesses. Forget the builder.</p>','published','2026-04-01T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('phnom-penh-first-year','What Phnom Penh teaches you in the first year','Power cuts, banking lines, and the weight of relationships before transactions.','Cambodia','cambodia',ARRAY['Cambodia','Phnom Penh','expat']::text[],'<p>The first year in Phnom Penh teaches you that nothing happens in the order you expect.</p><p>The power goes out during a Zoom call with a buyer in Lyon. The bank takes three weeks to open a corporate account, then the relationship manager who set it up moves to a different branch and you start again. The lawyer is excellent but he is also at a wedding in Battambang for four days. A truck of rice leaves the mill in Kampong Thom and arrives a day late because of road works no one announced.</p><p>For the first six months, you fight this. You write longer schedules. You add buffer. You learn to say the polite Khmer phrase for "is it ready" without meaning ready in the way you meant it last year.</p><p>Around month seven, something shifts. You stop building schedules and start building relationships. You realize that the lawyer at the wedding will pick up the phone for you on a Sunday because you went to his daughter''s blessing. You realize that the bank manager who moved branches still answers your WhatsApp because you helped her son with his English application. You realize that the truck arriving a day late is fine because the buyer in Lyon was always going to wait a week on customs anyway.</p><p>The infrastructure improves every year. The relationships are the infrastructure.</p><p>This is the thing the spreadsheets in Singapore miss. You cannot model Cambodian business on time and cost alone. You have to model on trust, and trust is built slowly, in person, over meals you did not plan and meetings that ran long because the conversation was worth it.</p><p>I am not romanticizing it. There are real costs. Foreigners who try to operate here on contracts alone burn time and money and leave. The ones who stay are the ones who learned to read a room in Khmer before they learned to read a contract.</p><p>If you are coming to Cambodia to build, learn the names first. The deals follow.</p>','published','2026-04-05T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('american-supermarket-test','The American supermarket test','Weekly sell-through at one Atlanta store is the only number that matters right now for Golden BRM Rice.','Business','cambodia',ARRAY['business','export','rice','BRM']::text[],'<p>There is a 15kg bag of Golden BRM Rice on a shelf in Norcross, Georgia.</p><p>It is in Hong Kong Supermarket, a regional Asian grocery chain that serves the Cambodian diaspora outside Atlanta. Benny is on the ground there. He sends us photos of the shelf, the placement, the price tag. He talks to the buyer. He notices when a competitor moves position. He watches what comes off the shelf and what stays.</p><p>For us, this is the test. Not the trade show in Bangkok. Not the LinkedIn announcement about export ambitions. The test is whether a Cambodian family in Georgia, walking through Hong Kong Supermarket on a Saturday, picks up our bag instead of the Thai or Vietnamese one they have bought for ten years.</p><p>The number that tells us if we are winning is weekly sell-through. How many bags moved through that one store in seven days. Not the total order. Not the shipment volume. Sell-through. Because total orders can be a buyer being generous on a first round. Sell-through is the customer choosing.</p><p>This is harder than it sounds for a Cambodian rice brand. The Cambodian-American community is smaller than the Thai or Vietnamese one. They are loyal to the brands their parents bought. The premium shelf space at Hong Kong Supermarket is competitive. Asian grocery is a margin business and the buyer needs us to move.</p><p>We are not trying to outspend anyone. We are trying to be the bag that a grandmother picks up because the packaging looks like it came from home, the price is fair, and her daughter said the rice cooked well last week. That is the loop. Grandmother, daughter, kitchen, repeat.</p><p>If weekly sell-through holds for three months, we expand to a second store. If it dips, we go back to the packaging, the price, the placement. We do not announce the expansion until the number says we can.</p><p>This is how a Cambodian brand earns the American shelf. One store. One number. One quiet month at a time.</p>','published','2026-04-10T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('label-is-not-a-brand','A label is not a brand','Working on the 110ml Moo Moo carton taught me to design for the hand, not the shelf.','Brand Building','cambodia',ARRAY['design','brand','dairy','Moo Moo']::text[],'<p>We spent three weeks on a 110ml carton.</p><p>It was the Moo Moo Farms x Nutifood collaboration, printed by LamiPak in Vietnam. The brief looked simple. A small carton of milk for Cambodian children. Khmer and English copy. The Moo Moo logo. A photo of a cow.</p><p>The first round of design was for the shelf. It was loud. The logo big, the colors saturated, the copy stacked on the front face. The reasoning was that a small carton has to fight to be seen in a fridge full of bigger competitors.</p><p>It tested badly. Parents picked it up and put it down. We watched at the Moo Moo Mart in Phnom Penh. The carton did not feel like milk for a child. It felt like a product trying to sell itself.</p><p>We started again. The second round was for the hand. Smaller logo. More white space. The cow photo softened. The Khmer copy given room. The English copy moved to the back. The price point did not change. The product inside did not change. Only the surface design changed.</p><p>It moved. Parents picked it up and held it. They turned it over. They put it in the basket.</p><p>This is the lesson I keep coming back to. A label is the surface of a product. A brand is what a person feels when they pick the product up. The label can fight for the shelf and still lose at the hand.</p><p>The shelf is a marketing problem. The hand is a brand problem. You can win the shelf with budget. You only win the hand with restraint.</p><p>LamiPak printed the second version. The cartons are in the market now.</p>','published','2026-04-14T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('gps-on-a-kampong-thom-paddy','GPS on a Kampong Thom paddy','How we monitor AWD and No Burn compliance for BRM farmers without turning them into a spreadsheet.','Agriculture','cambodia',ARRAY['agriculture','BRM','rice','technology']::text[],'<p>There is a Sentinel-2 satellite that passes over Kampong Thom every five days.</p><p>It takes a picture of the BRM Agro paddy fields at ten meter resolution. From that picture, we can see two things that matter for our investors and our buyers. We can see whether a field has been burned after harvest. And we can see, through NDVI, whether a farmer is keeping the field as wet as he says he is, or letting it dry between irrigation cycles. The dry cycle is called Alternate Wetting and Drying. It cuts methane and saves water. It is one of the practices we ask our farmers to follow.</p><p>The instance is called BRM Cambodia Basemap. It runs on Sentinel Hub. We pull NDVI layers and burn scar layers for every field we monitor.</p><p>This sounds clean on a slide. On the ground, it is messier.</p><p>Sok Im, our top performing farmer last season, does not need a satellite to tell him when his paddy is too dry. He has been reading those fields for thirty years. The satellite tells us, the office, the buyer, the auditor, what Sok Im already knows. The satellite is not for him. The satellite is for the people who need numbers to trust what farmers have been doing well for decades.</p><p>This is where I want to be honest. The technology helps us prove compliance to a French buyer or a German co-financing program. It does not improve Sok Im''s farming. It improves our story about Sok Im''s farming.</p><p>Sometimes those are the same thing. Sometimes they are not.</p><p>The phasing matters. Year one, we set up the system and learn to read the data. Year two, we start using the data to support the farmers, not to police them. Year three, the farmers see their own fields on a screen and start asking questions about water and soil that we did not know how to answer. That is when the satellite becomes useful to the paddy, not just to the office.</p><p>We are in year one. The system works. The credibility is honest. We are not oversold.</p>','published','2026-04-18T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('one-hundred-underfed-cows','One hundred underfed cows','What we inherited at Moo Moo Farms in 2024, and what 600 cows looks like in 2025.','Dairy','cambodia',ARRAY['dairy','Moo Moo','turnaround']::text[],'<p>When our group acquired Moo Moo Farms in 2024, we inherited just over one hundred cows. Most of them were underfed.</p><p>The farm was founded around 2015, the first commercial dairy in Cambodia. The idea was right. The execution had run out of capital. The cows had been on a thin ration for months. Production was a fraction of what the herd could deliver. The infrastructure was tired. The team was small and tired with it.</p><p>Patrick took the call on operations. I write the story. This is a useful division of labor, because the story of a turnaround is always less interesting than the operations, and Patrick is too busy with operations to romanticize them.</p><p>The first year was feed and bodies. Better ration, more consistent supply, slow rebuild of the herd. We did not buy our way out of the problem. We brought the existing animals up to weight first. A thin cow does not become a productive cow by adding a hundred more thin cows next to her.</p><p>By end of 2025, we expect to be around 600 cows. By end of 2026, around a thousand. These are the numbers we share with investors when they ask for the trajectory. They are not the numbers I think about day to day.</p><p>The number I think about day to day is whether the milk that leaves the farm in the morning is the same temperature when it arrives at the Moo Moo Mart in Phnom Penh in the afternoon. Cold chain. The most boring word in dairy. It is also the word that determines whether a Cambodian family can buy fresh local milk for their child for the same price as imported powder reconstituted in a factory.</p><p>We are not building a dairy empire. We are building a national supply chain, slowly, measured in bodies and grass. If it works, a thousand cows by 2026 is the start of a story about Cambodia growing its own food again. If it does not work, it is a hundred underfed cows that became a thousand underfed cows.</p><p>The bet is that it works. The work is feed, grass, cold chain, and patience.</p>','published','2026-04-23T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('king-white-elephant','King White Elephant','Why navy and gold, not red and gold. Why the elephant, not the dragon.','Rice','cambodia',ARRAY['rice','BRM','design','packaging']::text[],'<p>King White Elephant is the gift box version of BRM Agro''s premium rice, designed for Cambodian government officials. We deliver it in December 2026.</p><p>The design brief had one constraint that shaped everything. It could not look Vietnamese, Thai, or Chinese.</p><p>This sounds obvious. It is not. The visual grammar of premium Asian gift boxes is dominated by red, gold, dragons, and lotus motifs that read as generic Chinese New Year. A Cambodian official receiving a premium rice gift box from a Cambodian company should not, for a second, feel like he is unwrapping something from Hanoi or Bangkok or Guangzhou.</p><p>We went with royal navy and burnished gold. The navy is the color of the formal sampot, the high ceremonial dress of the Cambodian court. The gold is hot foil stamped, not printed. The closure is a rigid magnetic flap. The iconography is the white elephant, not the dragon. In Cambodian and broader Theravada culture, the white elephant is the symbol of royal lineage and Buddhist merit. It is the right animal for this gift, in this country.</p><p>The Khmer typography is set in a custom display cut. The English is a quiet serif underneath. The country of origin is large on the back. The brand is small on the front. The rice variety is on a separate inner card so the box reads as a gift first and a product second.</p><p>The whole thing took six months. Three rounds of physical prototypes. One trip to the printer to see the foil stamp at scale. A long argument about whether the elephant should face left or right. He faces left, toward the spine of the box, because elephants in Khmer ceremonial art traditionally face toward the dignitary, not away.</p><p>These are small decisions. They are also the entire job. A premium gift box that gets it wrong is worse than a plain bag of rice. A premium gift box that gets it right is a country saying something about itself.</p><p>We are not making this for the export market. We are making it for the Cambodian state. The export market will see it, eventually, and it will say more about Cambodian rice than any trade show.</p><p>December 2026. The boxes ship.</p>','published','2026-04-27T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('drinks-for-the-next-cambodian','Drinks for the next Cambodian','Seekers, Jason Kong, Wild Bong, Chanthy. Not for tourists. For the regional class that is arriving.','Spirits & Hospitality','cambodia',ARRAY['spirits','Seekers','hospitality','brand']::text[],'<p>The default assumption about a Cambodian craft spirit is that it is for tourists.</p><p>Pub Street in Siem Reap. A backpacker hostel in Phnom Penh. A bottle behind the bar at a riverside place that takes US dollars and serves a banana shake next to a rum. This is the market that a lot of Southeast Asian craft brands settle into, because tourists pay in cash and do not argue about price.</p><p>Seekers is not building for that market.</p><p>The portfolio is four brands so far. Seekers, the flagship. Jason Kong, the personal brand for our partner. Wild Bong, the wilder, looser expression. Chanthy, upcoming. Each one is built for a specific occasion and a specific Cambodian. None of them are built for a tourist who will be in Bangkok next week.</p><p>The customer we design for is the Cambodian who grew up here, studied abroad, and came back. The one who works in Phnom Penh now, who hosts dinners at home, who knows what a good Negroni tastes like and is tired of being told that good cocktails only exist in Bangkok or Singapore. The Cambodian-Australian who comes home for Pchum Ben and wants to take a bottle to her cousin. The expat who has been here long enough to know that the right gift for a Cambodian friend is a Cambodian bottle, not a French one.</p><p>This is a small market today. It is the market that is coming. The middle class in Cambodia is the fastest growing demographic the country has seen in fifty years. They are not waiting to be served by imports. They want their own thing.</p><p>Seekers Spirit House, the venue, is part of this. It is where the bottles meet the people. Not a tourist bar. A house, in the literal Cambodian sense, where you go because you know the owner and you trust the room.</p><p>The work is brand, design, and patience. Jun and Tania run the room. Sunny does the visuals. Marco and Linda are on the floor. I work on the story. The story is not "craft spirits from Cambodia." The story is that Cambodia is allowed to drink itself.</p><p>When you build for the next Cambodian, the tourists show up anyway. They are not the audience. They are the bonus.</p>','published','2026-05-01T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('filming-with-a-princess','Filming with a princess','How the TV5 Monde documentary France-Cambodge, Je t''aime, moi aussi came together.','Media & Talent','cambodia',ARRAY['media','royal','talent','documentary']::text[],'<p>In March 2026, Emmanuel Sheffer flew into Phnom Penh to film a segment for "France-Cambodge, Je t''aime, moi aussi" for TV5 Monde. He needed access to a member of the Cambodian royal family. I made the call.</p><p>The principal subject was Princess Jenna Norodom. The authorizing figure was Princess Bophary Norodom. Princess Rattana Norodom was in the conversation. Jenna''s team, Momo and Mr. Song, ran the day. My job was to make sure all of them said yes to the same project at the same time, and that the project showed up looking like what they had agreed to.</p><p>This is the part of the work that does not look like work. It looks like dinners. It looks like long messages on WhatsApp. It looks like a producer asking, three times, whether the wardrobe is approved.</p><p>A producer needs three things from a fixer in Cambodia. He needs access that holds. He needs to know what is actually happening in the room versus what is being said to him in English. He needs someone who will tell him, before he asks, that the schedule he sent is wrong and here is the schedule that will work.</p><p>A princess needs three things from a producer. She needs to be filmed as a person, not a costume. She needs the final cut to honor the agreement, not slip into the cliche of monarchy-as-curiosity for a Western audience. She needs the project to land in a way that her family can be proud of.</p><p>These three things, from each side, are usually compatible. Sometimes they are not. The work is to find the version of the project where they are.</p><p>The shoot went well. Emmanuel is a serious documentarian, not a tourist with a camera. Jenna gave him a real interview. The team around her, Momo and Mr. Song, worked with us instead of around us. The piece will air on TV5 Monde to a French and Francophone audience that, for most of them, will be their first long look at modern Cambodia through a Cambodian face.</p><p>I do not put my name on the credits. The credit is the trust that lets us make the next one.</p>','published','2026-05-06T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong'),
('the-rosewood-grid','The Rosewood grid','Why a hotel''s print magazine taught us more about social than any social tool did.','Design & Marketing','cambodia',ARRAY['design','social','Seekers','content']::text[],'<p>In May 2026, we needed a way to announce that Seekers was moving headquarters without actually saying so. The audience would lose interest in a corporate update. The team needed the visual energy of a fresh chapter without a press release.</p><p>The answer came from a Rosewood Hotel magazine.</p><p>I had picked one up months earlier in a lobby. It was the in-room edition, the kind of glossy bound volume that hotels of a certain class produce twice a year. The thing that struck me was the rhythm. Every six pages, the magazine ran a six-panel grid. Three photos on the left page, three on the right. No copy. No captions. Just six images that, together, said something the captions could not.</p><p>I took a photo of the spread. It sat in my Notes app for two months.</p><p>When the HQ move came up, I pulled it back out. We built the same six-panel grid for Instagram. Three posts in the top row, three in the second, set against the Seekers green palette. Each image fragmentary on its own. Together, when scrolled through, they read as a complete spread, like a magazine flipped open. We called it the HQ Move Interlude.</p><p>The grid did three things at once. It announced the move without announcing it. It rewarded the follower who scrolled the whole profile, not just the first post. And it set a visual rhythm for the next quarter, because once you have laid down a six-panel grid, the seventh image has to either continue the story or start a new one. There is no half-measure on a grid.</p><p>The lesson is not about Instagram. The lesson is that print magazines have been solving the visual narrative problem for a hundred years. Social tools are five years old. Most of what is taught as "content strategy" online is a poor copy of what a good art director knew in 1965.</p><p>When we look for new ideas for Seekers, Jason Kong, Wild Bong, and the rest of the portfolio, we look at print first. We look at fashion books, hotel magazines, the layout of a Wallpaper spread, the way a Comme des Garçons lookbook opens. Then we ask how that grammar translates to a feed.</p><p>The social tools change every six months. The grammar does not.</p>','published','2026-05-10T09:00:00+00:00','Sovandarapor Kong')
